{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505743"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2474"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2474"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.04,0.03,0.51,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56253"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2474"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41806"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42502"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56253"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of recurrent severe throbbing right-sided headaches. She experiences four headaches per month, each lasting several hours. During these episodes, she feels nauseated and has vomited on several occasions. In the hour preceding her headaches, she reports blurring of her vision and flashing lights in her peripheral fields.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe reports that each episode typically slowly resolves by taking diclofenac and resting in a dark and quiet room. However, they require her to take time off work, and she has exhausted her sick leave entitlements. She has not noted any particular pattern associated with her headaches. Her medical history includes generalised anxiety disorder. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her BMI is 20 kg/m2. Central and peripheral neurological examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate pharmacological prophylaxis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sumatriptan","Pregabalin","Sodium valproate","Propranolol","Carbamazepine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with recurrent episodes of long-lasting unilateral throbbing headaches associated with nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances, consistent with migraine. Migraine prophylaxis is indicated when headaches are frequent, long-lasting, or significantly impact daily life. This is especially relevant considering that the headaches are impacting the patient\u0027s ability to work. There are several options for first-line treatments for migraine prophylaxis; however, the patient\u0027s age, sex, and medical comorbidities can be used to determine the most suitable first-line agent for each patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, is a first-line option for migraine prophylaxis. It is effective in reducing the frequency and severity of migraine attacks. Propranolol works by blocking beta-adrenergic receptors, which can help stabilise blood vessel tone and reduce migraine frequency. Furthermore, it has the additional benefit of potentially improving her anxiety symptoms. Therefore, this is the most appropriate option in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium valproate\u003C/strong\u003E is also a first-line prophylactic treatment for migraines but is less suitable for women of childbearing age due to its teratogenic potential. It works by increasing gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) levels in the brain, which can help stabilise neuronal activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESumatriptan\u003C/strong\u003E is used for acute migraine attacks, not for prophylaxis. It acts as a selective agonist for serotonin receptors, leading to vasoconstriction of intracranial blood vessels, thereby alleviating migraine symptoms. Additionally, overuse of triptans can exacerbate migraines and lead to medication overuse headaches, therefore its use should be largely limited to acute migraine attacks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbamazepine\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for trigeminal neuralgia and is not indicated for migraine prophylaxis. It works by stabilising inactive sodium channels, reducing neuronal excitability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregabalin\u003C/strong\u003E lacks strong evidence for efficacy in migraine prophylaxis and is not typically used for this purpose. It works by binding to the alpha-2-delta subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels, reducing neurotransmitter release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, propranolol is the most appropriate choice for this patient due to its efficacy in migraine prophylaxis, potential benefits for her anxiety, and its safety profile in women of childbearing age. The choice of prophylactic treatment should always be individualised based on the patient\u0027s specific characteristics, comorbidities, and potential side effects of the medication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Propranolol is a first-line option for migraine prophylaxis, effective in reducing the frequency and severity of migraine attacks.","Migraine prophylaxis is indicated when headaches are frequent, long-lasting, or significantly impact daily life.","Beta-blockers like propranolol can have the additional benefit of improving anxiety symptoms in patients with comorbid anxiety disorders."],"references":["Migraine [updated 2019 Jan]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed March 7, 2024. https://www-tg-org-au.elibrary.jcu.edu.au","Tzankova V,  Becker WJ, Chan TLH. Pharmacologic prevention of migraine. CMAJ. 2023; 195:E187-E192."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41806"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2474"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41806"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T21:29:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T21:30:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2474"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56253"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela